
What is Ansible?
----------------

  -> Ansible is an open-source configuration management, software provisioning, and application deployment tool that makes automating your application deployments and 
    IT infrastructure operation very simple.
  
  -> Ansible is very lightweight, easy to configure, and is not resource hungry because it doesn’t need an agent to run (agentless) unlike other automation tools, for example,
  
  -> Puppet which is agent based and is a bit complex to configure.

Key Features and Concepts:
--------------------------

  => Agentless: No software agents are required on the managed nodes, reducing overhead.
    
  => YAML Playbooks: Defines automation tasks in easy-to-read YAML files.
    
  => Idempotency: Ensures that running the same playbook multiple times results in the same state, preventing unnecessary changes.
    
  => Modules: Ansible executes instructions via modules, which are small programs that do the actual work.
    
  => Inventory: A file defining the managed nodes (servers, network devices)

Common Use Cases:
-----------------

  => Configuration Management: Automating the configuration of servers, including installing packages and applying updates.
    
  => Application Deployment: Streamlining the deployment of applications across multiple environments.
    
  => Infrastructure Provisioning: Managing cloud instances, network configurations, and virtual machines.
    
  => Orchestration: Managing complex, multi-tier workflows across infrastructure.
